1.2 Statistical Transformations

group="whatever" is a dummy grouping to override the default behavior, which (here) is to group by cut and in general is to group by the x variable. The default for geom_bar is to group by the x variable in order to separately count the number of rows in each level of the x variable. For example, here, the default would be for geom_bar to return the number of rows with cut equal to Fair, Good, etc.

However, if we want proportions, then we need to consider all levels of cut together. In the second plot, the data are first grouped by cut, so each level of cut is considered separately. The proportion of Fair in Fair is 100%, as is the proportion of Good in Good, etc. group=1 (or group="x", etc.) prevents this, so that the proportions of each level of cut will be relative to all levels of cut.

ggplot(diamonds) +
  geom_bar(aes(cut, ..prop.., group = 1))

ggplot(diamonds) +
  stat_summary(
    aes(cut, depth),
    fun.ymin = min,
    fun.ymax = max,
    fun.y = median
  )

1.3 Exercises

In our proportion bar chart, we need to set group = 1. Why? In other words what is the problem with these two graphs?

ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = ..prop..))
ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_bar(
    mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = color, y = ..prop..)
  )

If we fail to set group = 1, the proportions for each cut are calculated using the complete dataset, rather than each subset of cut. Instead, we want the graphs to look like this:

ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = ..prop.., group = 1))

ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_bar(
    mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = color, y = ..prop.., group = color)
  )

  1. What time of day should you fly if you want to avoid delays as much as possible?
# , arr_delay dep_delay   .

zmad <- function(x) {
  (x - median(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / mad(x, na.rm = TRUE)
}

flights2 <- flights %>% 
  mutate(
    zmad_arr_delay = zmad(arr_delay),
    zmad_dep_delay = zmad(dep_delay)
  ) %>% 
  filter(abs(zmad_arr_delay) < 3.5, abs(zmad_dep_delay) < 3.5) %>% #  
  select(year:day, hour, carrier, flight, dest, dep_delay, arr_delay) %>% 
  group_by(month, hour) %>% 
  summarise(arr_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
            dep_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(flights2, aes(hour)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = arr_delay, colour = "arr_delay")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = dep_delay, colour = "dep_delay")) +
  facet_wrap(~month) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 12) +

  1. For each destination, compute the total minutes of delay. For each flight, compute the proportion of the total delay for its destination.
flights %>% 
  group_by(dest, flight) %>% 
  summarise(tot_arr_delay = sum(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
         tot_dep_delay = sum(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  group_by(dest) %>% 
  mutate(avg_arr_delay = tot_arr_delay / sum(tot_arr_delay),

4. Delays are typically temporally correlated: even once the problem that caused the initial delay has been resolved, later flights are delayed to allow earlier flights to leave. Using lag() explores how the delay of a flight is related to the delay of the immediately preceding flight.

flights %>%
  group_by(year, month, day, hour) %>%
  filter(!is.na(dep_delay)) %>%
  mutate(lag_delay = lag(dep_delay)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(lag_delay)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(lag_delay, dep_delay)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'
